# MEMOSPARK DE-SLOP MASTER RULES

memospark.live — live student productivity web app. Ghanaian students. Timetable, Crashout mood journal, Streaks, Stu AI assistant, Social/messaging, Stress game, Voice input. 20 GHS/month premium. Real users. Not a template.

---

# SECTION 1: MCP TOOL RULES — WHEN AND HOW TO USE EACH

## CONTEXT7 — Always use for library documentation

Every time you write code that uses an external library (React, Next.js, Supabase, Tailwind, Framer Motion, Zustand, React Query, Radix, Zod, date-fns, any npm package), you MUST:

1. Call resolve-library-id with the library name
2. Call get-library-docs with the resolved ID
3. Only then write code using that library

Never rely on training memory for API shapes, hook signatures, or config options. Libraries change. Training data lies. This is non-negotiable for every external dependency.

**Trigger:** Any import statement involving node_modules.

## DESIGN-INSPIRATION — Use before touching any UI

This MCP searches Dribbble, Behance, Awwwards, Mobbin, and Pinterest for real reference designs. It also extracts actual design tokens (colors, fonts, spacing, border-radius values) from any live website URL via headless browser.

Use it in TWO ways:

### Way 1 — Pull references before redesigning anything

Before touching any UI component, search for what great versions of that component look like in the real world:

- `design_search_images("student productivity app mobile dark")`
- `design_search_images("mood journal entry card interface")`
- `design_search_images("streak counter gamification mobile")`
- `design_search_images("onboarding flow student app minimal")`
- `design_search_images("achievement unlock notification mobile")`
- `design_search_styles("fintech dashboard west africa mobile")`

Then describe what you observe in those references before coding. Let the references visibly inform the implementation. Do not ignore them.

### Way 2 — Extract tokens from sites worth emulating

When you find a site whose design language fits MemoSpark, extract its exact tokens:

- `design_extract_tokens("https://example-site.com")`

This returns real hex values, font families, spacing units, and border-radius values. Use these as the foundation for whatever you're building — not guesswork.

**MANDATORY:** For any screen-level component or feature redesign, call design-inspiration BEFORE writing a single line of CSS or Tailwind. No exceptions.

**Suggested extraction targets (run these at session start):**

- `design_extract_tokens("https://duolingo.com")`
- `design_extract_tokens("https://notion.so")`
- `design_extract_tokens("https://linear.app")`
- `design_extract_tokens("https://arc.net")`

## PLAYWRIGHT — Live design mirror and de-slop verifier

Playwright gives you a real browser inside Cursor. Use it to:

### Before de-slopping any feature

- Navigate to production, screenshot — before state.

### After making changes, verify locally

- Navigate to `http://localhost:3000/[route]`, screenshot — compare to before.

### Extract computed CSS from any reference site

Navigate, then evaluate JS to read `getComputedStyle` on a representative element. Real computed values, not guesses.

### Audit heading hierarchy during de-slop

Evaluate: map `h1`–`h4` to tag + truncated text.

### Check colour contrast on any element

Evaluate: return text and background colors from computed style.

**RULE:** Playwright is not just for testing. It is the live visual feedback loop throughout this entire de-slop session.

## SEMGREP — Runs after every file edit, no exceptions

After every file you modify:

1. Call security_check on the modified file
2. Fix all findings silently before presenting code
3. Use get_abstract_syntax_tree before modifying any file whose structure you're not certain of — never guess

NEVER present code with unresolved security findings. NEVER add semgrep-ignore without explicit user approval and a written justification in the same line comment.

## ESLINT — Runs after every JS/TS/JSX/TSX edit

After every frontend file edit:

1. Run eslint on the changed file
2. Errors are blockers — fix before presenting
3. Warnings are fixed unless explicitly dismissed
4. Never add eslint-disable without explicit approval

Most common AI code failures eslint catches:

- useEffect with missing dependencies (#1 AI tell)
- Unused variables and imports left silently
- Implicit any on API responses
- Missing return types on async functions
- No-floating-promises

## GIT — Consult history before changing anything

Before modifying any existing file:

1. Call git_log on that file (last 15 commits minimum)
2. If a commit mentions a bug fix, read that diff before touching the code it affected
3. Call git_diff_unstaged before summarising what changed

A strange pattern usually exists for a reason. Check history before removing anything that looks unnecessary.

**Commit message format:**

- Imperative mood, max 72 chars, domain-specific

**BANNED:** "refactor code", "update files", "fix bug", "wip"

**REQUIRED examples:** "fix streak reset on midnight timezone rollover", "replace generic empty state with Crashout copy", "extract useTimetable hook, add error boundary"

## GITHUB — Search before creating anything

Before creating any component, hook, util, or helper:

1. Search the repo for existing implementations
2. If found: use it, extend via props if needed
3. If multiple versions exist: consolidate, don't add another

If Button, Modal, Card, Input, Badge, Toast, Spinner already exist in this codebase — USE THEM. Never create ButtonNew, ModalV2, CustomCard, or any fork of an existing component.

